# Condition contrasts

The model coefficients are relative to the reference condition, so I use contrasts to read the condition differences more directly. For value estimation, positive differences mean the first condition has **higher error** than the second condition. Since lower error is better, positive differences favor the second condition.

## Pairwise contrasts

```{r pairwise-contrasts}
emm_corr_group <- emmeans(m_corr, ~ lecture_type * practice_type)
emm_slope_group <- emmeans(m_slope, ~ lecture_type * practice_type)

pairwise_corr <- pairs(emm_corr_group, adjust = "tukey") |>
  clean_emm_comparison_table() |>
  mutate(Outcome = "Correlation") |>
  select(Outcome, everything())

pairwise_slope <- pairs(emm_slope_group, adjust = "tukey") |>
  clean_emm_comparison_table() |>
  mutate(Outcome = "Slope") |>
  select(Outcome, everything())

pretty_table(pairwise_corr, caption = "Pairwise comparisons: correlation absolute error")
pretty_table(pairwise_slope, caption = "Pairwise comparisons: slope absolute error")
```

```{r pairwise-plot, fig.height=5.5}
pairwise_plot_df <- bind_rows(pairwise_corr, pairwise_slope) |>
  mutate(
    Outcome = factor(Outcome, levels = c("Correlation", "Slope")),
    Contrast = fct_rev(Contrast)
  )

ggplot(pairwise_plot_df, aes(x = estimate_value, y = Contrast)) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", alpha = 0.6) +
  geom_errorbarh(aes(xmin = lower_value, xmax = upper_value), height = 0) +
  geom_point(aes(shape = p_value_numeric < .05), size = 2.5) +
  facet_wrap(~ Outcome, scales = "free_x") +
  scale_shape_manual(values = c(`TRUE` = 16, `FALSE` = 1), guide = "none") +
  labs(
    title = "Pairwise condition differences in value-estimation error",
    subtitle = "Positive values mean the first condition had higher error. Open circles are non-significant.",
    x = "Difference in mean absolute error",
    y = NULL
  ) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(color = "gray35")
  )
```

```{r pairwise-interpretation}
pairwise_all <- bind_rows(pairwise_corr, pairwise_slope)

n_sig_pairwise <- pairwise_all |>
  filter(!is.na(p_value_numeric), p_value_numeric < .05) |>
  nrow()

cat(
  '<div class="note-box">',
  '<p><strong>Pairwise read.</strong> The pairwise contrasts are mostly useful for locating the pattern, not for making a strong claim. ',
  'In this output, ', n_sig_pairwise, ' Tukey-adjusted pairwise comparison(s) are below .05. ',
